    </script><meta content="LearningHindi" property="fb:admins" /><meta content="Learning Hindi!" property="og:site_name" /><meta content="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/871458843/lesson-18-consonants-part-6-य-ya-र-ra-ल-la" property="og:url" /><meta content="article" property="og:type" /><meta content="Last time we saw the fifth group of consonants. Can you remember them? Check back here if you can&rsquo;t! We&rsquo;re nearly there now, this is the penultimate group! So are you ready to get going? Here&rsquo;s the letters we are going to be learning today&hellip;





 There&rsquo;s only four consonants in this group so it&rsquo;s going to be a little easier! This group is called the semivowels. Are you ready to get straight into it? Here goes then&hellip;


ya&nbsp; 




 This is the letter &#2351; ya. This letter is quite an easy one for an English speaker - it&rsquo;s pronounced just like a normal English &ldquo;y&rdquo; but slightly lighter. Use the audio above to hear it pronounced. Not only that but this letter even looks like an English Y!





 The Hindi word &#2351;&#2366;&#2352; yaar means &ldquo;friend&rdquo; or &ldquo;pal&rdquo; and it&rsquo;s a word you&rsquo;re going to hear all the time! Can you spot our new letter &#2351; ya here? Awesome! You can hear the word pronounced above. Ready to move on?


 ra&nbsp; 




 This is the letter &#2352; ra. This pronunciation may be a little tricky. It&rsquo;s pronounced as a slightly trilled &ldquo;r&rdquo; - like the &ldquo;r&rdquo; in Spanish but lighter. Use to audio above to listen to the letter. It even looks a little like an &ldquo;r&rdquo; too, easy!





 The word for &ldquo;night&rdquo; in Hindi is &#2352;&#2366;&#2340; raat. Can you spot our new letter here? Nice one!


 The consonant&nbsp;&#2352;&nbsp;ra&nbsp;is a bit special because the two vowels&nbsp;&#2313;&nbsp;u&nbsp;and&nbsp;&#2314;&nbsp;oo&nbsp;join on to it slightly differently. Here&rsquo;s how it works:&nbsp;&#2352;&nbsp;ra +&nbsp;&#2313;&nbsp;u&nbsp;gives us&nbsp;&#2352;&#2369;&nbsp;ru&nbsp;and&nbsp;&#2352;&nbsp;ra +&nbsp;&#2314;&nbsp;oo&nbsp;gives us&nbsp;&#2352;&#2370;&nbsp;roo. Can you see that these are a tiny bit different to what me might expect? Good!&nbsp;Let&rsquo;s keep going then.


 la&nbsp; 




 This is the letter &#2354; la. This letter sounds quite like a normal English &ldquo;l&rdquo; sound, like in the word um&hellip; &ldquo;like&rdquo;! The Hindi pronunciation is a little lightly than English &ldquo;l"s - so use the audio above to help you.





 The Hindi word for "red&rdquo; is &#2354;&#2366;&#2354; laal. Our new letter appears twice here! Can you spot it? Good! You can learn more about Hindi colours in Lesson #47 here. Are you ready for the final letter of this group then?


va&nbsp; 




 This is the letter &#2357; va. This is a tricky letter so full concentration! This letter usually sounds half way between the English letter &ldquo;v&rdquo;, like in &ldquo;vest&rdquo;, and the letter &ldquo;w&rdquo;, like in &ldquo;west&rdquo;, which you can hear in the audio above. But in some words it floats closer to a &ldquo;v&rdquo; or a &ldquo;w&rdquo; sound! It can be tricky to get right.





 On example word where this letter sounds more like a &ldquo;v&rdquo; is &#2361;&#2357;&#2366; havaa which means &ldquo;wind&rdquo; in Hindi. Have a listen to the word above. Can you spot &#2357; va here? Remember that this letter usually sounds half way between &ldquo;v&rdquo; and &ldquo;w&rdquo; but in some words sounds more like a certain one of them!


 Well there we go! That&rsquo;s another group of consonants you&rsquo;ve mastered. Well done! Be sure to practice writing them down and saying them out loud. There&rsquo;s only one more group of consonants left now - you can check them out here!


