        (document.getElementsByTagName('HEAD')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('BODY')[0]).appendChild(s);
    }());
</script></aside><h2><a href="lesson-18-consonants-part-6-and">Lesson #18: Consonants Part 6; य ya, र ra, ल la and व va </a></h2><div class="caption clearfix rte"><p>Last time we saw the fifth group of consonants. Can you remember them? <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/858244745/lesson-16-consonants-part-5-pa-pha-ba-bha">Check back here</a> if you can&rsquo;t! We&rsquo;re nearly there now, this is the penultimate group! So are you ready to get going? Here&rsquo;s the letters we are going to be learning today&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/547671c0d921d639df68d639c4bef760/tumblr_inline_mnzbqxg96K1qz4rgp.png"></p><p>There&rsquo;s only four consonants in this group so it&rsquo;s going to be a little easier! This group is called the semivowels. Are you ready to get straight into it? Here goes then&hellip;</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/b4fae7deee5d8d18ba5def6523bc4393/tumblr_inline_mnzby3FYw11qz4rgp.png"><em>ya&nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F96552998&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2351;</big></big> <em>ya</em>. This letter is quite an easy one for an English speaker - it&rsquo;s pronounced just like a normal English &ldquo;y&rdquo; but slightly lighter. Use the audio above to hear it pronounced. Not only that but this letter even looks like an English Y!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/a1bcaab611bbd7653ea72abbfba001e0/tumblr_inline_mnzckgltsw1qz4rgp.png"></p><p>The Hindi word <big><big>&#2351;&#2366;&#2352;</big></big> <em>ya</em>ar means &ldquo;friend&rdquo; or &ldquo;pal&rdquo; and it&rsquo;s a word you&rsquo;re going to hear all the time! Can you spot our new letter <big><big>&#2351;</big></big> <em>ya</em> here? Awesome! You can hear the word pronounced above. Ready to move on?</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/33c0aae6f2c49b53edb633af1af98c35/tumblr_inline_mnzcp9nudf1qz4rgp.png"><em> ra&nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F96553097&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2352;</big></big> <em>ra</em>. This pronunciation may be a little tricky. It&rsquo;s pronounced as a slightly trilled &ldquo;r&rdquo; - like the &ldquo;r&rdquo; in Spanish but lighter. Use to audio above to listen to the letter. It even looks a little like an &ldquo;r&rdquo; too, easy!</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/48090b153c3ad4e256ff3154c940efef/tumblr_inline_mnzfdvKVZ41qz4rgp.png"></p><p>The word for &ldquo;night&rdquo; in Hindi is <big><big>&#2352;&#2366;&#2340;</big></big> <em>raat</em>. Can you spot our new letter here? Nice one!</p><p>The consonant&nbsp;<big><big>&#2352;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ra</em>&nbsp;is a bit special because the two vowels&nbsp;<big><big>&#2313;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>u</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<big><big>&#2314;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>oo&nbsp;</em>join on to it slightly differently. Here&rsquo;s how it works:&nbsp;<big><big>&#2352;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ra +</em>&nbsp;<big><big>&#2313;</big></big><em>&nbsp;<em>u</em>&nbsp;</em>gives us&nbsp;<big><big>&#2352;&#2369;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ru</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<big><big>&#2352;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>ra +</em>&nbsp;<big><big>&#2314;</big></big><em>&nbsp;<em>oo</em>&nbsp;</em>gives us&nbsp;<big><big>&#2352;&#2370;</big></big>&nbsp;<em>roo</em>. Can you see that these are a tiny bit different to what me might expect? Good!&nbsp;Let&rsquo;s keep going then.</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/a72574cb2427df1fbcf6378bf6349f58/tumblr_inline_mnzffmBOFe1qz4rgp.png"><em> la&nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F96553142&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2354;</big></big> <em>la</em>. This letter sounds quite like a normal English &ldquo;l&rdquo; sound, like in the word um&hellip; &ldquo;like&rdquo;! The Hindi pronunciation is a little lightly than English &ldquo;l"s - so use the audio above to help you.</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/305ae394022a7123281a42d4d6a54358/tumblr_inline_mnzfulPzNM1qz4rgp.png"></p><p>The Hindi word for "red&rdquo; is <big><big>&#2354;&#2366;&#2354;</big></big> <em>laal</em>. Our new letter appears twice here! Can you spot it? Good! You can learn more about Hindi colours in <a href="../1098745517/lesson-47-colours-rang">Lesson #47 here</a>. Are you ready for the final letter of this group then?</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/aa1500501d3f0370547843f67de7ce86/tumblr_inline_mnzfygsagI1qz4rgp.png"><em>va&nbsp;</em> <iframe align="middle" frameborder="no" height="70" scrolling="no" src="http://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fapi.soundcloud.com%2Ftracks%2F96553226&amp;%20%20auto_play=false&amp;show_artwork=false&amp;color=000000&amp;show_user=false&amp;%20%20show_playcount=false&amp;sharing=false&amp;show_comments=false" width="26%"></iframe></p><p>This is the letter <big><big>&#2357;</big></big> <em>va</em>. This is a tricky letter so full concentration! This letter usually sounds half way between the English letter &ldquo;v&rdquo;, like in &ldquo;vest&rdquo;, and the letter &ldquo;w&rdquo;, like in &ldquo;west&rdquo;, which you can hear in the audio above. But in some words it floats closer to a &ldquo;v&rdquo; or a &ldquo;w&rdquo; sound! It can be tricky to get right.</p><p class="center"><img alt="image" src="http://78.media.tumblr.com/43f82b1040c98ea4e7e5de52742a6f66/tumblr_inline_mnzgowXpK21qz4rgp.png"></p><p>On example word where this letter sounds more like a &ldquo;v&rdquo; is <big><big>&#2361;&#2357;&#2366;</big></big> <em>havaa </em>which means &ldquo;wind&rdquo; in Hindi. Have a listen to the word above. Can you spot <big><big>&#2357;</big></big> <em>va</em> here? Remember that this letter usually sounds half way between &ldquo;v&rdquo; and &ldquo;w&rdquo; but in some words sounds more like a certain one of them!</p><p>Well there we go! That&rsquo;s another group of consonants you&rsquo;ve mastered. Well done! Be sure to practice writing them down and saying them out loud. There&rsquo;s only one more group of consonants left now - you can check them out <a href="http://t.umblr.com/redirect?z=http%3A%2F%2Flearning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F908470587%2Flesson-23-consonants-part-7-and&amp;t=ZmRlM2NkM2RjZTI5N2ZjZjE2NWE3ZGZiMmRiMzNhNGQ4ZjBmNmViMCxpcGNPVWdTdw%3D%3D&amp;b=t%3Ahf3yIetu6VvjxJqY6DH92g&amp;p=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.learning-hindi.com%2Fpost%2F871458843%2Flesson-18-consonants-part-6-%E0%A4%AF-ya-%E0%A4%B0-ra-%E0%A4%B2-la&amp;m=0">here</a>!</p><p><a href="../../consonants">Back to the Consonants Section</a>.&nbsp;</p></div><aside class="post-footer"><div class="tags"><span>Tags:</span><a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/ya">ya</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/ra">ra</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/la">la</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/va">va</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/consonants">consonants</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/july2010">july2010</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/devangari">devangari</a> <a href="http://www.learning-hindi.com/tagged/letters">letters</a> </div><div class="bottom"><div class="like_button" data-post-id="871458843" data-blog-name="learninghindi" id="like_button_871458843"><iframe id="like_iframe_871458843" src="http://assets.tumblr.com/assets/html/like_iframe.html?_v=5716f9145cbbcc5e21aa13229de5d4ed#name=learninghindi&amp;post_id=871458843&amp;color=grey&amp;rk=ipcOUgSw" scrolling="no" width="16" height="16" frameborder="0" class="like_toggle" allowTransparency="true" name="like_iframe_871458843"></iframe></div><a href="https://www.tumblr.com/reblog/871458843/ipcOUgSw" class="reblog_button"style="display: block;width:16px;height:16px;"><svg width="100%" height="100%" viewBox="0 0 21 21" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" fill="#ccc"><path d="M5.01092527,5.99908429 L16.0088498,5.99908429 L16.136,9.508 L20.836,4.752 L16.136,0.083 L16.1360004,3.01110845 L2.09985349,3.01110845 C1.50585349,3.01110845 0.979248041,3.44726568 0.979248041,4.45007306 L0.979248041,10.9999998 L3.98376463,8.30993634 L3.98376463,6.89801007 C3.98376463,6.20867902 4.71892527,5.99908429 5.01092527,5.99908429 Z"></path><path d="M17.1420002,13.2800293 C17.1420002,13.5720293 17.022957,14.0490723 16.730957,14.0490723 L4.92919922,14.0490723 L4.92919922,11 L0.5,15.806 L4.92919922,20.5103758 L5.00469971,16.9990234 L18.9700928,16.9990234 C19.5640928,16.9990234 19.9453125,16.4010001 19.9453125,15.8060001 L19.9453125,9.5324707 L17.142,12.203"></path></svg></a><div class="share button">Share<div class="share-box"><div class="label">Share this:</div><a class="twitter button" href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=http://www.learning-hindi.com/post/871458843/lesson-18-consonants-part-6-य-ya-र-ra-ल-la" target="_blank">Twitter</a><a class="pinterest button" target="_blank">Pinterest</a><a class="facebook button" href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=http://www.learning-hindi.com/p